{
  "query": "What are the documented effects of adding soil amendments like charcoal, sulphur, or carbon before or after seeding on grassland vegetation?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents, the documented effects of adding specific soil amendments before or after seeding on grassland vegetation are as follows:\n\n**Carbon amendments**: Two studies in the USA found that adding carbon to soil after sowing seeds either reduced or did not alter the density of sown forb species (Action 3433).\n\n**Charcoal amendments**: One study in the Netherlands found that adding charcoal to soil before sowing seeds did not alter overall plant biomass or grass cover, but increased the cover of legumes while not affecting the cover of other forbs (Action 3422).\n\n**Sulphur amendments**: Studies in the UK and USA showed mixed effects when adding sulphur before seeding. One study found reduced plant species richness while another found no change in overall plant species richness (Action 3428). Adding sulphur before sowing reduced overall vegetation cover in one UK study, but increased the cover of three of six sown species when low amounts were used (Action 3428). Native plant species cover and richness were not altered by sulphur addition in a USA study (Action 3428). When sulphur was added alongside seeding in UK studies, it did not increase heather cover in most cases, had mixed effects on common heather, perennial rye-grass, and common bent cover, but increased heather seedling survival though survival remained very low after two years (Action 1710).",
