{
  "query": "What are the potential negative or neutral effects of adding amendments like mulch or carbon to the soil when seeding grasslands?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents, several potential negative or neutral effects of adding amendments like mulch or carbon to soil when seeding grasslands have been documented:\n\nCarbon amendments: Two replicated, randomized, controlled studies in the USA found that adding carbon to soil after sowing seeds either reduced or did not alter the density of sown forb species (Action 3433).\n\nMulch amendments show mixed and often neutral effects: One replicated, controlled study in Germany found that adding mulch before sowing seeds did not alter the species richness of target plants (Action 3425). One replicated, controlled study in Canada found that adding mulch before sowing seeds did not increase plant cover (Action 3425). One of two replicated, randomized, controlled studies in the USA and UK found that adding mulch before sowing seeds did not alter the density of six sown plant species in most cases, while the other study found that adding mulch before planting seedlings reduced the cover of planted species (Action 3425). One replicated, randomized, controlled study in the UK found that adding mulch before planting seedlings did not alter the cover of common knapweed (Action 3425). One replicated, randomized, controlled study in the USA found that adding mulch after planting native prairie plants did not alter the growth of any of seven plant species (Action 3425).\n\nCharcoal amendments generally showed neutral effects: One replicated, randomized, paired, controlled study in the Netherlands found that adding charcoal to soil before sowing seeds did not alter overall plant biomass and did not alter grass cover (Action 3422).\n\nFertilizer amendments can have negative effects on growth: One replicated, randomized, controlled study in the USA found that adding fertilizer after planting native prairie plants reduced the diameter of prairie lupine plants and did not alter the growth of six other plant species (Action 3427).",
