{
  "query": "Which site preparation techniques appear most effective at increasing species richness before seeding in European grasslands?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on European grassland restoration studies, soil disturbance appears to be the most effective site preparation technique for increasing species richness before seeding. Action 3413 reports that one of two replicated, controlled studies in the UK and Germany found that disturbing soil before sowing seeds increased plant and seedling species richness, and a UK study found that rotovating soil before sowing seeds increased both grass and forb species richness in most cases compared to harrowing before sowing. Four of five replicated, controlled studies found that disturbing soil before sowing seeds increased plant emergence in most cases compared to sowing alone.\n\nOther site preparation techniques showed mixed or limited effectiveness for species richness. Adding sulphur to soil before seeding had negative effects, with Action 3428 showing that one UK study found adding sulphur to soil before sowing seeds reduced plant species richness and overall vegetation cover, though low amounts of sulphur increased the cover of three of six sown species. \n\nMycorrhizal inoculation showed minimal benefits for species richness, as Action 3429 reports that one replicated, randomized, controlled study in Germany found that inoculating soil with mycorrhizal fungi and sowing seeds of grassland species did not alter plant species richness.\n\nThe broader context from Action 133 indicates that 20 European studies found restoring species-rich grassland resulted in higher plant species richness than other types of grassland, with effective techniques including grazing, introducing plant species, hay spreading and mowing.",
  "action_ids": [
    "3413",
    "3428",
    "3429",
    "133"
  ]
}

